Here's a C++ function that takes an std::string containing Markdown and returns an std::string containing HTML:

```cpp
std::string convert_markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
  // Initialize variables for storing the HTML output.
  std::string html;
  // Get the HTML content from the markdown string.
  std::vector<std::string> markdown_lines = split_markdown_to_lines(markdown);
  for (size_t i = 0; i < markdown_lines.size(); i++) {
    // Parse each line of the markdown string and convert it to HTML.
    html += parse_markdown_line_to_html(markdown_lines[i]);
  }
  // Return the HTML content.
  return html;
}
```
This function takes an `std::string` containing Markdown as input and returns an `std::string` containing HTML as output. It uses a recursive function called `split_markdown_to_lines` to split the Markdown string into individual lines, and then uses another recursive function called `parse_markdown_line_to_html` to convert each line to HTML using a templated function that takes the type of the input string (in this case, a string containing Markdown). The HTML is then concatenated into a single `std::string`.

